  "market_context": "EUR/USD and DXY are inversely correlated. The analyst marks corresponding highs and lows on both charts within a defined range to identify SMT divergences, then steps forward in replay to observe how each divergence resolves into a reversal.",
  "key_observation": "When inversely correlated assets fail to mirror each other (e.g. EUR makes a higher low but DXY makes a higher low instead of a lower high), an SMT divergence is present and signals a high-probability reversal in the expected direction.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Explain the inverse correlation rule — a high on DXY should correspond to a low on EUR/USD, and a higher high on DXY should correspond to a lower low on EUR/USD.",
    "Step 2: Open the dual-panel DXY and EUR/USD 1H charts and confirm the inverse relationship by pointing out that a low on DXY corresponded with a high on EUR/USD.",
    "Step 3: Mark out the same highs and lows on both charts to define the range used for SMT comparison.",
    "Step 4: Step the replay forward and identify the first SMT — EUR/USD forms a higher low while DXY forms a higher low (instead of the expected lower high), signaling a reversal which then plays out.",
    "Step 5: Identify a second SMT — DXY fails to take a prior high while EUR/USD does take its corresponding low, creating divergence and another reversal (DXY down / EUR up).",
    "Step 6: Identify a third SMT at the 10 a.m. low — EUR has caught up but does not take the matching high on DXY initially; after a brief reversal attempt, DXY ultimately fails, takes the high, and continues lower, confirming the SMT-based reversal."
  ],
  "outcome": null,
  "lessons": "On inversely correlated pairs, look for mirrored structure; any divergence (one asset failing to make the opposite move) is a valid SMT and frequently precedes a reversal in the expected direction.",
